definition.value: The R-enantiomer of adrenaline. It is a hormone secreted by the adrenal glands resulting in the 'fight-or-flight' response.
The 3-beta-D-glucuronide of estrone.
A glyco-amino acid compound consisting of an N-acetyl-alpha-D-muramoyl group attached to L-alanine via an amide linkage.
Adenine substituted with a methyl group at position N-7.
A prostaglandins Falpha that is prosta-5,13-dien-1-oic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 9, 11 and 15. It is the 9beta-hydroxy epimer of prostaglandin F2alpha.
An aminophenol that is one of three amino derivatives of phenol which has the single amino substituent located meta to the phenolic -OH group.
A flavonoid phytoalexin that is (S)-naringenin in which the hydroxy group at position 7 is replaced by a methoxy group.
An adenosine 3'-phosphate with a monophosphate group at the 3'-position.
A C18, straight-chain, hydroxy fatty acid composed of linoleic acid having an (R)-hydroxy group at the 8-position.
An oxaspiro compound that is(5beta,25R)-spirostan substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3.
A vitamin D supplement and has been isolated from alfalfa.
A hexadec-2-enoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (E)-hexadec-2-enoic acid.
A lysophosphatidylethanolamine obtained by selective hydrolysis of the 1-acyl substituent of any 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine.
The (1'R)-(-) enantiomer of abscisic acid, which does not occur naturally.
An onium cation obtained by protonation of ammonia.
An  N-acetyl-L-amino acid that is the N-acetylated derivative of the natural amino acid L-cysteine.

A mixture of rac-methyl 6-(4-isopropyl-4-methyl-5-oxo-2-imidazolin-2-yl)-m-toluate and rac-methyl 6-(4-isopropyl-4-methyl-5-oxo-2-imidazolin-2-yl)-p-toluate in the ratio 3:2. A proherbicide (by ester hydrolysis) for imazamethabenz, it is used to control grasses and other weeds in winter cereal crops.

A hydroxy seco-steroid that is (5Z,7E)-9,10-secocholesta-5,7,10(19)-triene in which the pro-S hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a hydroxy group. It is the inactive form of vitamin D3, being hydroxylated in the liver to calcidiol (25-hydroxyvitamin D3), which is then further hydroxylated in the kidney to give calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3), the active hormone.
A straight-chain, C22, long-chain saturated fatty acid.
A CDP-D-glucose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A ceramide phosphoethanolamine in which the sphingoid component is specified as sphing-4-enine (sphingosine).

A dimethylxanthine having the two methyl groups located at positions 3 and 7. A purine alkaloid derived from the cacao plant, it is found in chocolate, as well as in a number of other foods, and is a vasodilator, diuretic and heart stimulator.
An organosulfonic acid that consists of 5-oxo-2-furylacetic acid bearing a sulfo group at position 2.
An aminoalkylindole that is indole carrying a dimethylaminomethyl substituent at postion 3.

A nitramine that is methylamine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a nitro group while the other is substituted by a 2,4,6-trinitrophenyl group. A yellow crystalline powder, it is a high explosive, capable of being detonated by friction, shock, or a spark.
A C21-steroid hormone that is 5alpha-pregnane substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 20. It is a metabolite of progestrone.
A 17beta-hydroxy steroid, being 17beta-estradiol methoxylated at C-2.
A dicarboxylic acid that is cis,cis-muconic acid in which the hydrogens at position 3 is substituted by a methyl group.
A piperidine compound having a 2-(4-methoxyphenyl)ethyl group at the 1-position and an N-[(4-fluorobenzyl)benzimidazol-2-yl]amino group at the 4-position.
Any sugar having one or more alcoholic hydroxy groups replaced by substituted or unsubstituted amino groups.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of phenoxyacetic acid.
A carboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any dicarboxylic acid.
A family of magnesium porphyrins, defined by the presence of a fifth ring beyond the four pyrrole-like rings. The rings can have various side chains which usually include a long phytol chain.
A tryptamine derivative having two N-methyl substituents on the side-chain.
A triterpenoid saponin that is cycloastragenol with a 2-O-beta-D-glucopyranosyl-beta-D-xylopyranosyl moiety attached at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
